\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}%ЁАsec:introЁБ ЪЧИјИУНкЕФУќУћЃЈПЩЛЛЦфЫћЃЉЃЌв§гУЪБгУ\ref{sec:intro}

The $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B reaction plays a crucial role in constraining the properties of neutrino oscillations and solar composition through solar-neutrino experiments~\cite{ade11,hax13} since $^8$B is the major source of the high-energy solar neutrinos. Recent experiments were able to determine the neutrino flux emitted from $^8$B decay with a precision of 9\%~\cite{ahm04}, while the theoretical predictions have uncertainties of the order of 20\%~\cite{bah04}. Theoretical neutrino flux critically depends on the $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B reaction.

The $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B reaction also plays an important role in the evolution of the first stars which formed at the end of the cosmic dark ages \cite{bro04}. Various simulations suggest that the first stars could have appeared between 100 and 250 million years after the Big Bang. A classic question on the evolution of these supermassive stars is whether they contributed any significant material to later generations of stars by supernova explosions. In 1986, the evolution of non-rotating supermassive stars was studied with a hydrodynamic code KEPLER \cite{ful86} which concluded that these stars will collapse into black holes without experiencing a supernova explosion. This is
because the triple alpha process (3$\alpha \rightarrow $ $^{12}$C)
does not produce sufficient amounts of CNO seed nuclei so that the
hot CNO cycle and rp-process are unable to generate the nuclear
energy enough to explode the stars. In 1989, the rap-processes were suggested as alternative paths which would permit these stars to bypass the 3$\alpha$ process
and to yield the CNO material \cite{wie89}. The $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B reaction is one of the key reactions in these rap-processes.

Due to its importance, the $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B reaction has increasingly attracted both theoretical and experimental studies in past years. As for the experiment, the direct measurements were performed with the proton beam on the $^7\textrm{Be}$ target~\cite{fil83l,bab03l,jun03,fil83c}, or with the radioactive $^7$Be beam on the H$_2$ target~\cite{ter01,gia00}. In addition, indirect measurements were carried out through Coulomb dissociation method~\cite{bau86,iwa99,dav01,sch06,sch03} and the transfer reaction method~\cite{wpliu96,oga03,das06,azh06}. As for the theoretical side, several methods were utilized, including the R-matrix parametrization ~\cite{bar95}, the potential model ~\cite{rob73,typ97},  the microscopic cluster models ~\cite{des94,cso95,des04}, and the ab initio calculations ~\cite{nav06,nav11}.

In this work, we derive the neutron asymptotic normalization coefficient (ANC) for the virtual decay $^8\textrm{Li} \rightarrow$ $^7\textrm{Li} +$ n by reanalysing the existing angular distribution of the $^{7}\textrm{Li}$(d,\,p)$^{8}\textrm{Li}$ reaction at $E_d$=12~MeV \cite{sch67} based on the distorted wave Born approximation (DWBA) and adiabatic wave approximation (ADWA) approaches, and then deduce the proton ANC for the virtual decay $^8\textrm{B} \rightarrow $ $^7\textrm{Be} +$ p based on charge symmetry of mirror nuclei. The $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B astrophysical S-factors and reaction rates of direct capture into ground state of $^8\textrm{B}$ are then obtained. We have also calculated the contributions from the $1^+$ and $3^+$ resonances at $E_x$ = 0.774 MeV and 2.320 MeV. The relationship of the ANCs for mirror systems has been well established~\cite{tim03,tim05}, and successfully utilized to study the $^8$B(p,\,$\gamma$)$^9$C, $^{11}$C(p,\,$\gamma$)$^{12}$N and $^{26}$Si(p,\,$\gamma$)$^{27}$P reactions \cite{guo05,guo06,guo07}.

\section{The neutron ANC for virtual decay $\bm{^8\textrm{Li}$$_{g.s.}$ $\rightarrow}$ $^7$Li + n}

When the $^{7}\textrm{Li}$(d,\,p)$^{8}\textrm{Li}$ reaction is measured at conditions when it is peripheral, such as at sufficiently low incident energies, the single neutron ANC of $^8\textrm{Li}_{g.s.}$ $\rightarrow$ $^7$Li + n can be extracted by matching the theoretical calculations (in this work, we use the DWBA and ADWA methods) to the experimental differential cross sections:
\begin{equation}\label{eq1}
(\frac{\textrm{d}\sigma}{\textrm{d}\Omega})_{\exp}=\sum\limits_{j_ij_f}(C_{l_ij_i}^d)^2(C_{l_fj_f}^{^8\textrm{Li}})^2R_{l_ij_il_fj_f},
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}\label{eq2}
R_{l_ij_il_fj_f}=\frac{\sigma_{l_ij_il_fj_f}^{DWBA}}{(b_{l_ij_i}^d)^2(b_{l_ij_i}^{^8\textrm{Li}})^2},
\end{equation}
$(\frac{\textrm{d}\sigma}{\textrm{d}\Omega})_{\exp}$ and $\sigma_{l_ij_il_fj_f}^{DWBA}$~are the experimental and theoretical differential cross sections, respectively. $C_{l_ij_i}^d$, $C_{l_fj_f}^{^8\textrm{Li}}$, $b_{l_ij_i}^d$ and $b_{l_ij_i}^{^8\textrm{Li}}$ represent nuclear and corresponding single-particle ANCs for virtual decays of d $\rightarrow$ p + n and $^8$Li $\rightarrow$ $^7$Li $+$ n, respectively. $l_i$, $j_i$ and $l_f$, $j_f$ are the orbital and total angular momenta of the transferred neutron in d and $^8$Li, respectively. $R_{l_ij_il_fj_f}$ is model independent under the condition of peripheral transfer reaction.

