In this work, theoretical calculations of the transfer cross sections are made with the finite-range DWBA method using the computer code FRESCO \cite{ian88}. The optical potential parameters used in the DWBA calculation are listed in Table \ref{tab:table1}, which were taken from Ref.~\cite{sch67}.

To include the breakup effects of deuteron in the entrance channel, the transfer cross sections are also calculated within the Johnson-Soper adiabatic approximation to the neutron, proton and target three-body system \cite{joh70,wal76}. The adiabatic distorting potential governing the centre-of-mass motion of the deuteron is well described by the sum of the neutron- and proton-target optical potentials. Hence this method is called the adiabatic wave approximation (ADWA). In the present calculation, the optical potentials of nucleon-target are taken from Ref. \cite{var91} (ADWA1) and Ref. \cite{kon03} (ADWA2).

$C_d^2$ is taken to be 0.76 fm$^{-1}$ from Ref.~\cite{blo77}. Two components, corresponding to the neutron transfers to the 1$p_{1/2}$ and 1$p_{3/2}$ orbits, contribute to the $^{7}\textrm{Li}$(d,\,p)$^{8}\textrm{Li}_{g.s.}$ reaction. The ratio $(C^{^8\textrm{Li}}_{p_{1/2}})^2$/$(C^{^8\textrm{Li}}_{p_{3/2}})^2$ is taken to be 0.13(2) from Ref. \cite{tra03}. In Fig.~\ref{fig:figure1} we display the resulting DWBA and ADWA angular distributions of the $^{7}\textrm{Li}$(d,\,p)$^{8}\textrm{Li}$ reaction with these four sets of optical potential parameters, together with the experimental data. In order to verify if the $^{7}\textrm{Li}$(d,\,p)$^{8}\textrm{Li}$ reaction is peripheral, the ANCs and spectroscopic factors are calculated using the different geometry parameters of the Woods-Saxon potential for the single-particle bound state with the DWBA1 optical potential, as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:figure2}. One see that the spectroscopic factors vary significantly, while the ANCs are nearly a constant, indicating the $^{7}\textrm{Li}$(d,\,p)$^{8}\textrm{Li}_{g.s.}$ reaction is dominated by peripheral process at the present energy.

