\section{The proton ANC for virtual decay $^8$B$_{g.s.}$ $\rightarrow$ $^7$Be + p}

The proton ANC of $^8\textrm{B}$ can be extracted from the neutron ANC of $^8\textrm{Li}$. The relationship between the proton ANC of $^8\textrm{B}\rightarrow$$^7\textrm{Be} +$ p and the neutron ANC of $^8\textrm{Li} \rightarrow$$^7\textrm{Li}$ + n can be expressed as
\begin{equation}\label{eq3}
(C_{l_fj_f}^{^8\textrm{B}})^2=R(C_{l_fj_f}^{^8\textrm{Li}})^2,
\end{equation}
where the ratio $R$ can be computed with \cite{tim03,tim05}
\begin{equation}\label{eq4}
R=|\frac{F_l(ik_pR_N)}{k_pR_Nj_l(ik_nR_N)}|^2,
\end{equation}
where $F_l$ and $j_l$ are the regular Coulomb wave function and the spherical Bessel function, respectively. The wave numbers of proton and neutron $k_p$ ($k_n$) are determined by the proton (neutron) separation energy $\varepsilon_p$($\varepsilon_n$) via $k=(2\mu\varepsilon/\hbar^2)^{1/2}$.

On the other hand, if we assume that the single-particle spectroscopic factors $S_p$ and $S_n$ are approximately equal for mirror system, the ANC ratio $R$ can also be derived with (based on the relationship of spectroscopic factor and ANC,  $C_{p(n)}=\sqrt{S_{p(n)}}b_{p(n)}$)
\begin{equation}\label{eq5}
R = \frac{(b_{l_fj_f}^{^8\textrm{B}})^2}{(b_{l_fj_f}^{^8\textrm{Li}})^2},
\end{equation}
where the single-particle ANCs $b_{l_fj_f}^{^8\textrm{B}}$ and $b_{l_fj_f}^{^8\textrm{Li}}$ can be derived from the single-particle wave functions calculated with the optical potential model. The ratio $R$ is then extracted to be $1.13$ and $1.03$ from equations \ref{eq4} and \ref{eq5}, respectively. We use the same geometry parameters $r_0$ and $a$, the same spin-orbit interaction for Woods-Saxon potential, and the depths adjusted to reproduce the neutron or proton binding energy in $^8\textrm{Li}$ or $^8\textrm{B}$.

The average of above two ratios is derived to be 1.08 $\pm$ 0.07. The squared ANCs for $^8$B$_{g.s.}$ $\rightarrow$ $^7$Be + p are then derived to be $(C_{p3/2}^{^8\textrm{B}})^2 = 0.51 \pm 0.08$ fm$^{-1}$, $(C_{p1/2}^{^8\textrm{B}})^2 = 0.066 \pm 0.011$ fm$^{-1}$ and $(C_{total}^{^8\textrm{B}})^2 = 0.57 \pm 0.10$ fm$^{-1}$. The error results from the uncertainties of the ANC $(C_{l_fj_f}^{^8\textrm{Li}})^2$ and the ratio $R$.

\section{The astrophysical S-factors and reaction rates of $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B}

At the temperatures of astrophysical interest, the direct capture into the $^8\textrm{B}$ ground state proceeds mainly by the E1 transition from the incoming s- and d-waves to the bound p state. In the present work, the direct capture cross sections and astrophysical S-factors are computed based on the proton ANC for $^8$B$_{g.s.}$ $\rightarrow$ $^7$Be + p by using the RADCAP code \cite{ber03}, which is a potential model tool for direct capture reactions.

The S-factors for the captures via the $1^+$ and $3^+$ resonances at $E_x$ = 0.774 MeV and 2.320 MeV are calculated with Breit-Wigner formula,
\begin{equation}\label{eq6}
\begin{aligned}
S_{res}(E)=&\pi \frac{(\hbar c)^2}{2{\mu c}^2} \frac{2J+1}{(2J_1+1)(2J_2+1)}\\
&\times\frac{\Gamma_p(E)\Gamma_{\gamma}(E)}{(E-E_R)^2+(\Gamma _{\textrm{tot}}/2)^2}\exp(\frac{E_G}{E})^{1/2} ,
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
where $E_R$ represents the resonance energy, $J$, $J_1$ and $J_2$ are the spins of $^8\textrm{B}$, proton and $^7\textrm{Be}$, respectively; $\Gamma _p$, $\Gamma _\gamma$ and $\Gamma _{\textrm{tot}}$ are the proton-, gamma- and total widths. The energy dependence of these widths is given by \cite{rol88}
\begin{equation}\label{eq7}
\Gamma _p(E) = \Gamma_p(E_R)\frac{\exp[-(E_G / E)^{1/2}]}{\exp[-(E_G/E_R)^{1/2}]} ,
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}\label{eq8}
\Gamma _{\gamma}(E) = \Gamma_{\gamma}(E_R)\frac{(Q+E)^{2l+1}}{(Q+E_R)^{2l+1}} ,
\end{equation}
where $Q$ is the reaction $Q$ value and $l$ represents the multipolarity of the $\gamma $ transition, $E_G = 0.978Z^2_1Z^2_2\mu$ MeV is the Gamow energy. The widths used in our calculation are $\Gamma_{p}(E_R)$ = 37 $\pm$ 5 keV and $\Gamma_{\gamma}(E_R)$ = 25 $\pm$ 4 meV \cite{fil83c} for the $1^+$ resonance and $\Gamma_{p}(E_R)$ = 350 $\pm$ 40 keV \cite{ajz88} and $\Gamma_{\gamma}(E_R)$ = 150 $\pm$ 30 meV \cite{jun03} for the $3^+$ resonance.

\begin{figure}[H]%ЁА[]ЁБжаЮЊЮЛжУВЮЪ§ЃЌЫФИіВЮЪ§tbph вРДЮЪЧжУЖЅЁЂжУЕзЁЂИЁЖЏЁЂЕБЧАЮЛжУЃЌЃЌбЁгУЕФВЮЪ§гХЯШЫГађЮЊh-t-b-p
\centering
\includegraphics[scale=0.45]{Sfactor.eps}%"scale" КѓЕФЪ§зжЮЊЭМаЮЕФПэЖШЃЌвВПЩгУ"width=1.0\columnwidth" ЖЈвх
\caption{(Color online) Astrophysical S-factor for the $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B reaction. The experimental data are taken from Refs. \cite{fil83c,hamm98,bab03c,hamm01,str01,jun10}.} % ЭМЬт
\label{fig:figure3}%{}жаЁАfig:example1ЁБЮЊЭМУћЃЌв§гУЪБгУ\ref{fig:example1}
\end{figure}

In Figure~\ref{fig:figure3} we show the present S-factors of the direct capture and the $1^+$ and $3^+$ resonances and total S-factors, together with the experimental data from Refs. \cite{fil83c,hamm98,bab03c,hamm01,str01,jun10}. It is seen that the present S-factors well reproduce the experimental data for a wide energy range between 0.1 MeV to 2.5 MeV. The direct capture S-factor at zero energy S$_{17}$(0) is then found to be 19.9 $\pm$ 3.5 eV b. In Figure~\ref{fig:figure4} we compare the present S$_{17}$(0) factor with the recommended values \cite{eri98,ade11}, as well as the previous results from direct measurements \cite{fil83l,hamm98,bab03l,jun10}, transfer reactions \cite{wpliu96,das06,azh06,oga03}, Coulomb dissociation experiments \cite{moto94,iwa99,sch03} and charge symmetry method \cite{tra03,howe13}. One can see that the present result agrees with the most recent recommended values \cite{eri98,ade11}, and presents an independent examination to the current results of the $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B reaction.

