For convenience, we fit our rate with the expression used
in the astrophysical reaction rate library REACLIB \cite{rau01}
\begin{equation}\label{eq14}
\begin{aligned}
N_A=&\exp[134.565-0.352308T_9^{-1}-63.0447T_9^{-1/3}\\
&-209.006T_9^{1/3}+13.1645T_9-0.6858T_9^{5/3}\\&+83.7921\ln(T_9)]
+\exp[12.4283+0.00154438T_9^{-1}\\&-10.4908T_9^{-1/3}-0.0172274T_9^{1/3}+0.266666T_9\\
&-0.0429832T_9^{5/3}-0.860093\ln(T_9)] ,
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
The fitting errors are smaller than $5\%$ over the range from $T_9$ =0.003 to $T_9$ =10.

\section{Summary and conclusion}

Transfer reaction is an effective approach to determining nuclear ANCs and then to investigating astrophysical S-factors and/or reaction rates \cite{xu94,azh99,li10,li11}. In this work we reanalyze the angular distribution for the neutron transfer reaction $^7$Li(d,\,p)$^8$Li leading to the ground state of $^8$Li, and derive the neutron ANC of the virtual decay $^8$Li $\rightarrow$ $^7$Li + n. According to charge symmetry, the proton ANC of $^8$B $\rightarrow$ $^7$Be + p is extracted and used to compute the S-factor and the reaction rate of the direct capture in the $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B reaction. We also evaluate the contributions from the $1^+$ and $3^+$ resonances. The present result demonstrates that the direct capture dominates the $^7$Be(p,\,$\gamma$)$^8$B reaction in the whole temperature range of $T_9$ = 0.003-10, especially at temperatures of $T_9 \leq 0.5$ the direct component accounts for more than 99.5\%. The new rate is about 20\% slower than the REACLIB compilation, while is in agreement with the NACRE rate, especially in good agreement with the most recent compilation of NACRE II. This work provides an independent examination to the current results for this reaction.

